larify what you mean by “source”?</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/uoQkZaX</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[onushka]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>this video just pissed me off so much</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/yDkQSNy</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/53UIFrR.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/yDkQSNy</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Formicula]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>A Moment of Humanity Amidst the Darkness</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/E3ojmuw</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/0BHgq1L.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>When U.S. troops liberated Dachau in April 1945, they entered a landscape of starvation and despair so profound that words could hardly capture the suffering. Amidst the survivors, one man lay so frail he couldn’t even lift a spoon to his lips.

An American soldier knelt beside him, lifting spoonfuls of broth to the man’s mouth. “Don’t give up,” he whispered gently. “I’ll help you eat.”

For that prisoner, the simple act of feeding him was more than just sustenance—it was the first time in years he was seen not as a number, but as a human being, a brother.

The survivors of Dachau carried memories like this with them for the rest of their lives—how a quiet act of compassion, food offered slowly, and words spoken softly, meant just as much as liberation itself.

It’s a powerful reminder: history isn’t only written in battles or declarations, but also in the tender moments when one person chooses humanity in the face of cruelty.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/E3ojmuw</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Mapconsuela]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Who had a 1-mile wide tornado on their bingo card?</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/l97FWig</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/gNhSN3v.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>I lived in the Midwest for about a decade.     I learned some things about tornados during my residency there.  

If you're staring at a tornado, and it doesn't look like it's moving along the ground, that means that it's heading straight for you, and you should probably de-ass the area with priority.    

This tornado was just designated as an EF5, as of this morning.   This is the first tornado of this magnitude in North Dakota since 1957.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/FUZCfHb.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This was the doppler echo, shamelessly pulled from Wikipedia.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/AMUbn6S.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This was the path of the tornadoes (yes there were three of them that night.)    If it would have formed about 90 seconds sooner, it would have forced itself straight through the town of Enderlin, ND.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ZzKUM9E.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>A closeup of the path.    The red line was the ground path left behind in its wake.   The pink areas around that line experienced winds close to 210mph.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/375ZP4X.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This was the rail that was tagged.  If you note the bright stripe of dirt next to the 130 ton train cars, you'll see the physical path that it took.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/l97FWig</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[MayMyEnemiesLiveLong]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>AMAZING goalie work</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/gbZTsuU</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/vYZo2uM.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/gbZTsuU</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Kyzyl]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Nothing to do - low morale and boredom.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/3Oa7SMX</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/NotSkEi.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.c